We can find $f$ up to an arbitrary constant by integrating $f'(x)$.

\begin{align*}
f(x) &= \int (\frac{1}{\sqrt{x}} + x^2) dx\\
&= \int (x^{-1/2} + x^2) dx\\
&= 2x^{1/2} + \frac{x^3}{3} + C\end{align*}

Imposing that $f(1) = 2$, we must have $2 + 1/3 + C = 2$ or that
$C = -1/3$.

The final answer is:

\begin{align*}f(x) = 2 \sqrt{x} + \frac{x^3}{3} - 1/3.\end{align*}
